 "name": "galton-board",
 "nodes": [
  {
   "id": "note",
   "type": "Note",
   "params": {
    "text": "GALTON BOARD - the normal distribution, fallen out of gravity\\n\\nEvery ball meets the same question at every row: left or right. One ball is\\nnoise. Sixty of them add up to a bell - not because anything draws one, but\\nbecause there are more ways to come down the middle than down a side.\\n\\nThere is no code in this graph. The board IS the nodes: a diamond Box, an\\nArrayLinear across and another down = one lattice; the same lattice moved half\\na spacing over and one row down = the stagger. Random + Range + ConstructPoint\\nscatter the balls. Everything static is wired into the ONE `container` socket.\\n\\nThe pegs are DIAMONDS on purpose. On a round peg a ball can sit balanced on\\ntop forever (friction holds it there) and only the balls flung sideways ever\\nreach a bin - the \"bell\" comes out hollow. An apex forces a choice. The bin\\ndividers get an apex too: a flat 1.6mm top is a ledge, and a ball WILL perch\\non it. Every horizontal surface a ball can rest on is a hole in the histogram.\\n\\nKnobs worth turning:\\n  grip (on Drop)  - how slippery the world is, and the knob that decides\\n                    whether you get a bell AT ALL: at 1 a sloped face grabs a\\n                    ball and flings it at the wall (two lumps, hollow middle);\\n                    at 0.15 it slides off and the walk is fair. Measured\\n  peg Box w/d     - fatter pegs deflect harder and jam the gaps\\n  array counts    - more rows = more coin flips = a wider, smoother bell\\n  Random count    - one ball is chance, sixty is a law (and `seed` re-runs the\\n                    same experiment: the bell survives, the lumps move)\\n  material        - clay lands dead; rubber makes it a pinball machine\\n  blade Move x    - slide the blade and the whole distribution moves with it\\n  timeline        - scrub the fall. With Live on it replays while you drag\\n\\nThe cost of having no code: the bins and walls do NOT follow the peg sliders.\\nWiden the lattice and you must widen them by hand - that coupling is the one\\nthing a CodeBlock buys you."
   },
